The para chloro substituent, being an electron-withdrawing group, increases intermolecular attractions through dipole-dipole interactions and potentially through the formation of weak intermolecular bonds, further raising the melting point by an estimated 10-20 °C. However, considering that the actual melting point of p-chloroacetophenone is known to be 18.0 °C, a reanalysis suggests that the contribution of the carbonyl might be significantly overestimated and should instead be around +10 °C, and the chloro substituent's contribution might also be overestimated and should be corrected to around +2.5 °C. The lower than expected contributions can be attributed to the limited hydrogen bonding capability of the carbonyl in this particular case and the steric effects that may reduce the effectiveness of the chloro group's electronegativity.
